00:11:56.169 --> 00:11:58.141
&gt;&gt; Gary: Well, I thought that it would be.
One of my

00:11:58.141 --> 00:12:03.450
inspirations was Orwell's 1984. The two big
novels – the great

00:12:03.450 --> 00:12:07.070
dystopian novels – obviously are Huxley's
Brave New World and

00:12:07.070 --> 00:12:11.260
Orwell's 1984. In some ways, as a novel of
ideas, Brave New World is

00:12:11.260 --> 00:12:17.370
a lot more fascinating. He predicted so many
things. SOMA which is our Valium mixed with

00:12:17.370 --> 00:12:20.750
Klonopin
mixed with I don't know what. So much of what

00:12:20.750 --> 00:12:24.459
Huxley
predicted came true. Orwell really took Stalin's

00:12:24.459 --> 00:12:30.681
Russia and Stalin's Soviet
Union and took it to 11. But I remember 1984

00:12:30.681 --> 00:12:34.509
a lot more
than I do Brave New World because of the characters

00:12:34.509 --> 00:12:37.040
--
because it's a love story. Winston and Julia

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:39.180
are in love
and there's this society trying to pry them

00:12:39.180 --> 00:12:45.529
apart. What
I thought I would do for this book -- they're

00:12:45.529 --> 00:12:47.740
in love,
but there's no need for a big brother because

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:50.329
everyone is
sort of deputized to chronicle their lives

00:12:50.329 --> 00:12:53.180
at all times.
The government doesn't need to spy into your

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:55.329
bedroom ,
because everyone in this society constantly

00:12:55.329 --> 00:12:57.709
updates where they
are, what they're doing, who they're sleeping

00:12:57.709 --> 00:13:01.600
with, what
kind of sex they enjoy. And everywhere you

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:04.840
go these
streams are everywhere around you. I sort

00:13:04.840 --> 00:13:08.490
of thought
what would an Orwellian future look like without

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:10.220
the
government actually controlling things.

00:13:10.220 --> 00:13:15.200
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And what made you decide
to write this from a diary

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:17.830
and personal memoir kind of standpoint. So
you have

00:13:17.830 --> 00:13:21.139
Lenny writing the diary and Eunice -- it's
kind of like

00:13:21.139 --> 00:13:27.390
through her global teens account which is
a mix of e-mail

00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:29.649
and chat and Twitter type messages.

00:13:29.649 --> 00:13:32.589
&gt;&gt; Gary: Yeah, in fact one of the challenges
was because

00:13:32.589 --> 00:13:35.899
Eunice -- well Eunice is one of the smartest
people in

00:13:35.899 --> 00:13:38.790
this future, because she can still write in
complete

00:13:38.790 --> 00:13:42.170
sentences which is very rare. Lenny calls
her 'my

00:13:42.170 --> 00:13:44.870
reluctant sentence monger' because she has
a subject and a

00:13:44.870 --> 00:13:50.050
predicate, usually, and he's really impressed
by that. Again it's an

00:13:50.050 --> 00:13:53.160
illiterate future, I have to make these characters
somewhat

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:56.320
literate so that the literate audiences in
Brooklyn and

00:13:56.320 --> 00:14:00.639
Seattle can enjoy this book. [laughter] And
that was tough to do, to

00:14:00.639 --> 00:14:03.770
sort of walk that fine line between her being
talking in

00:14:03.770 --> 00:14:06.920
this -- what's one acronym. TIMATOV, I think
I'm about to

00:14:06.920 --> 00:14:11.600
openly vomit. [laughter] Between that and
trying to write a

00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:14.300
literary novel -- well, there are a lot of
pitfalls.

00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:17.410
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: And what was it like
getting inside her head

00:14:17.410 --> 00:14:19.840
considering you've written male characters
before.

00:14:19.840 --> 00:14:25.639
&gt;&gt; Gary: So male, so male. [laughter] It was
great. It was actually very

00:14:25.639 --> 00:14:29.019
very liberating to be inside the mind of somebody
who's

00:14:29.019 --> 00:14:32.990
from a different mind set than my own; who's
from a

00:14:32.990 --> 00:14:36.009
different gender obviously, different race,
different --

00:14:36.009 --> 00:14:39.149
the only thing that was -- that felt familiar
to me in

00:14:39.149 --> 00:14:41.279
writing the Eunice character was that she
was a daughter

00:14:41.279 --> 00:14:45.910
of immigrants with all the nightmarish stuff
that come packaged

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:49.100
with the crazy parents insisting you should
do this and

00:14:49.100 --> 00:14:54.051
that. Even in this future where law isn't
much of a

00:14:54.051 --> 00:14:58.690
career choice. There's only three careers
left -- media,

00:14:58.690 --> 00:15:02.300
retail and credit; those are the three careers.
But her mother is still pushing her

00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:05.470
to take the LSAT hoping she'd go to law school.
[laughs]

00:15:05.470 --> 00:15:08.380
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: That sounds like Korean.
I'm Korean. I'm from southern California.

00:15:08.380 --> 00:15:09.940
I'm you know
it's funny.

00:15:09.940 --> 00:15:12.120
&gt;&gt; Gary: Well then. You're the perfect demographic.

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:16.130
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: This sounds really, really
familiar. I mean, aside

00:15:16.130 --> 00:15:17.770
from the abusive father. I didn't have an
abusive

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:18.770
father.

00:15:18.770 --> 00:15:22.130
&gt;&gt; Gary: You missed out on a lot. Those are
the best. They're

00:15:22.130 --> 00:15:24.740
really great motivators. [laughter]
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Oh well. [giggles] That's

00:15:24.740 --> 00:15:26.930
too bad.
&gt;&gt;Gary: Succeed or else. It's really

00:15:26.930 --> 00:15:29.079
funny when I do readings often and couples
come up to

00:15:29.079 --> 00:15:32.329
me -- "I'm Lenny." And the woman is like,
""and I'm

00:15:32.329 --> 00:15:33.329
Eunice."

00:15:33.329 --> 00:15:34.329
[laughter]

00:15:34.329 --> 00:15:37.959
&gt;&gt;Gary: And the Lenny says all she does is
shop online all day

00:15:37.959 --> 00:15:38.959
long.
[laughs]

00:15:38.959 --> 00:15:41.310
&gt;&gt; Gary: And she's like, "yeah, that's what
I do."

00:15:41.310 --> 00:15:42.310
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: yeah, that's me

00:15:42.310 --> 00:15:46.500
&gt;&gt;Gary: I'm like
you guys are the best. Thank you for existing.

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:49.509
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: And yeah, another book
I read recently was My Korean

00:15:49.509 --> 00:15:50.509
Deli by Ben Ryder Howe.

00:15:50.509 --> 00:15:53.360
&gt;&gt;Gary: I want to see that; I want to read
that. [laughs] I want to stream that.

00:15:53.360 --> 00:15:55.820
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: I think that's interesting
because the two books I

00:15:55.820 --> 00:16:00.589
happen to read about the Korean American culture
were written by

00:16:00.589 --> 00:16:04.220
non-Koreans. I thought that was interesting.
I think

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:07.300
you've kind of toed the line from writing
from what you

00:16:07.300 --> 00:16:11.690
know, writing part of your experience and
then also kind

00:16:11.690 --> 00:16:16.089
of examining another culture. What did you
find to be

00:16:16.089 --> 00:16:18.529
the benefit of either approach?

00:16:18.529 --> 00:16:21.970
&gt;&gt; Well, I went to Stuyvesant so Koreans [laughs]
I have known all

00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:26.199
my life. In fact, most of my best friends
were Koreans

00:16:26.199 --> 00:16:30.380
growing up because of Stuyvesant. And then
my mentor was

00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:35.070
Chang-Rae Lee, the Korean American author.
So this isn't a culture I

00:16:35.070 --> 00:16:38.870
approach with sort of -- it's one I know well
and I love

00:16:38.870 --> 00:16:40.649
Korea, I love Seoul. I think it's one of the
most

00:16:40.649 --> 00:16:44.910
fascinating cities. I like the confluence
between Soviet Jewish

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:47.899
families and Korean American families. I think
there's a lot of

00:16:47.899 --> 00:16:52.720
similarity in that both ethnic groups have
experienced a

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:57.769
horrific 20th century. Both are small groups
within a

00:16:57.769 --> 00:17:01.529
larger context. The Soviet Jews were a small
oppressed

00:17:01.529 --> 00:17:05.470
group within Russia, Ukraine and other places.
Korea was a

00:17:05.470 --> 00:17:11.220
once colonized group surrounded by Japan,
parents who are

00:17:11.220 --> 00:17:13.960
completely obsessed about academic achievement.
I mean,

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:16.340
many ethnic groups obviously share that as
well but I think here

00:17:16.340 --> 00:17:21.130
there's a particular brand of insanity and
the love of

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:23.600
cabbage is very important to both people.
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah, yes, absolutely

00:17:23.600 --> 00:17:26.640
&gt;&gt;Gary: Although I have to say the
Koreans do a much better job by adding spice

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:27.640
to it.

00:17:27.640 --> 00:17:29.750
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Yeah, kimchi. It's pretty
good. I can't lie.

00:17:29.750 --> 00:17:33.020
&gt;&gt;Gary: Kimchi is not bad.
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah.

00:17:33.020 --> 00:17:37.790
You've created an incredibly vivid world with
this novel.

00:17:37.790 --> 00:17:41.560
And is there anything that you weren't able
to include

00:17:41.560 --> 00:17:42.640
that you had dreamed of.

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:46.820
&gt;&gt; Gary: Sure. Well, I mean, the book kind
of became an

00:17:46.820 --> 00:17:49.960
obsession for me because I was starting to
be sucked into

00:17:49.960 --> 00:17:53.860
the technological world. I mean, starting
with Google

00:17:53.860 --> 00:17:56.760
really. I used to do a lot of my research
by going to

00:17:56.760 --> 00:17:59.370
the Slavic section of the New York public
library in

00:17:59.370 --> 00:18:03.120
forty-second street where I would catch the
most exotic Uzbek Flus

00:18:03.120 --> 00:18:04.410
and whatnot.

00:18:04.410 --> 00:18:05.590
[laughter]

00:18:05.590 --> 00:18:10.000
&gt;&gt; Gary: But then when Google came along,
all that stopped. I

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.870
never left my home. I stopped socializing.
[laughter] And so, each

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:17.180
new layer of the technology -- the iTelephone
-- the

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:22.240
Facebook, follow me on Facebook and Twitter.

00:18:22.240 --> 00:18:24.660
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Yeah, I noticed you had
accounts for both.

00:18:24.660 --> 00:18:29.340
&gt;&gt; Gary: I started Twitter two months ago.
Now I never leave

00:18:29.340 --> 00:18:34.830
home. [laughter] So, you know, I notice that
this technology was

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:37.100
taking over my life. It was also making it
difficult to

00:18:37.100 --> 00:18:40.950
concentrate on long form texts -- like books.
It's very

00:18:40.950 --> 00:18:42.590
difficult for me to read a 500-page book..

00:18:42.590 --> 00:18:43.590
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:45.370
&gt;&gt;Gary: I constantly get books to blurb. I
don't even

00:18:45.370 --> 00:18:48.780
read them anymore. I just blurb them. It's
just too hard.

00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:51.350
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Are they turning smelly?
Have you noticed that.

00:18:51.350 --> 00:18:54.280
&gt;&gt; Gary: The smell is the best part; I love
it. Books are like fine wines age very

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:56.000
well. And I have a lot of books from the Soviet
Union

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:59.920
growing up and they smell terrific. Much better
than

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:05.430
many of the people who sold them to us. So
you know I

00:19:05.430 --> 00:19:07.820
notice that my life was changing. Although
I'm not

00:19:07.820 --> 00:19:10.500
exactly in the, you know, what do they call
-- the early

00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:14.070
adapters -- I'm always the last adapter. Even
so I

00:19:14.070 --> 00:19:17.560
noticed my life was becoming more online.
That I was

00:19:17.560 --> 00:19:21.030
concerned with things that were very different
than

00:19:21.030 --> 00:19:24.640
before. Before I just basically wanted to
find space and

00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:28.300
time to write. But now I was sort of writing
all the

00:19:28.300 --> 00:19:31.570
time, because the moment I walk out of anything
I start

00:19:31.570 --> 00:19:35.260
typing on my iPhone. And that makes writing
a book --

00:19:35.260 --> 00:19:38.780
you're thinking, "well, I write all day long.
How is

00:19:38.780 --> 00:19:41.550
this different?" It also makes-- since books
are going

00:19:41.550 --> 00:19:45.330
digital -- it makes a different dynamic for
a book. It's

00:19:45.330 --> 00:19:49.550
no longer an object, and to some of us, a
sacred object. It's now a text file. One of

00:19:49.550 --> 00:19:52.040
the many text files that's being sent across
the

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:55.020
Internet. So coping with this stuff has been
very

00:19:55.020 --> 00:19:59.450
difficult for me. I think most writers fall
into my

00:19:59.450 --> 00:20:01.080
camp. There are some writers that are very
excited about

00:20:01.080 --> 00:20:04.040
the technology. But I haven't seen -- what's
interesting

00:20:04.040 --> 00:20:08.340
to me also is I teach at Columbia at the MFA
level and

00:20:08.340 --> 00:20:11.530
everyone wants to be a writer there, obviously.
And I

00:20:11.530 --> 00:20:15.380
noticed that a lot of my students do not have
-- the

00:20:15.380 --> 00:20:18.320
technology is often missing from their work.
So they'll

00:20:18.320 --> 00:20:21.420
have a story where people, you know, people
are out on a

00:20:21.420 --> 00:20:23.350
date and they're not texting their friends
about how the

00:20:23.350 --> 00:20:26.060
date is going. To me, that's surprising because
it seems --

00:20:26.060 --> 00:20:29.070
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Are they disconnecting?
Are they purposely not

00:20:29.070 --> 00:20:30.210
getting smart phones.

00:20:30.210 --> 00:20:32.740
&gt;&gt;Gary: I think they have this technology
that there's

00:20:32.740 --> 00:20:35.320
something sweet about this. They know how
endangered

00:20:35.320 --> 00:20:38.240
their mode of communication is by the new
technology that

00:20:38.240 --> 00:20:41.020
they almost want to go back to the kind of
novel where

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:45.250
people would run to a pay phone and put in
25 cents and

00:20:45.250 --> 00:20:47.260
dial their mother which never happens.
[laughter]

00:20:47.260 --> 00:20:50.870
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: There is a recent article
in the times by Pico Iyer about the

00:20:50.870 --> 00:20:54.280
joy of quiet. Did you see that? Just about
how with all

00:20:54.280 --> 00:20:57.160
this technology around us, how do we disconnect.
How do

00:20:57.160 --> 00:21:00.350
we find those moments of quiet? And even at
Google, we have a training class

00:21:00.350 --> 00:21:04.180
called "managing your energy." It's like sleep
more, you

00:21:04.180 --> 00:21:06.760
know, make sure you leave -- you close your
laptop and

00:21:06.760 --> 00:21:09.670
don't check your phone when you roll over
and look at it

00:21:09.670 --> 00:21:10.670
first thing in the morning.

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:12.540
&gt;&gt; Gary: First thing in the morning, I wake
up three in the

00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:17.371
middle of the night and look at it. It's horrible.
The

00:21:17.371 --> 00:21:20.390
only thing I've found I have a little cabin
up state and I go up

00:21:20.390 --> 00:21:27.621
there. AT&amp;T will not connect my itelephone
up there. Thanks

00:21:27.621 --> 00:21:29.940
to our country's crummy infrastructure, I'm
able to

00:21:29.940 --> 00:21:33.540
actually [laughter] -- this wouldn't happen
in Korea, believe me.

00:21:33.540 --> 00:21:36.400
I'm able to escape the constantly being connected
by

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:37.400
doing that.

00:21:37.400 --> 00:21:40.780
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Okay. Has your writing
process changed like before

00:21:40.780 --> 00:21:43.200
and after the technology entered it?

00:21:43.200 --> 00:21:47.130
&gt;&gt; Gary: It's gotten worse. I'm -- as I said
-- I'm not able.

00:21:47.130 --> 00:21:50.390
A lot of writing is also reading. A lot of
writing is

00:21:50.390 --> 00:21:52.450
saying for three hours a day I'm not going
to do anything

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:55.430
but read a book. And that book -- whatever
it is you're

00:21:55.430 --> 00:21:57.370
reading. It could be the classics. It could
be

00:21:57.370 --> 00:22:00.620
something by one of the brilliant young authors
we have

00:22:00.620 --> 00:22:05.490
these days. You interact with
it. It becomes part of you. Reading is basically

00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:08.890
saying I'm going to leave my own
personality for awhile and enter the consciousness

00:22:08.890 --> 00:22:10.770
of
another human being. That's actually pretty

00:22:10.770 --> 00:22:13.580
advanced
technology for being 500 years old or however

00:22:13.580 --> 00:22:16.780
old the
book is. And that's becoming increasingly

00:22:16.780 --> 00:22:19.710
hard to do to develop
that sense of empathy. Because everything

00:22:19.710 --> 00:22:21.320
is screaming
for my attention. It's like I'm at a party

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:22.770
where
everyone is saying “hey look at me; look

00:22:22.770 --> 00:22:27.770
at me; look at me.” So my
writing is hampered by my lack of sustained

00:22:27.770 --> 00:22:31.020
reading. And
that's why going up state and turning -- well

00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:32.960
I can't
turn it off. It just doesn't work. I have

00:22:32.960 --> 00:22:35.750
to go on this
mountain and on top of a bear on top of a

00:22:35.750 --> 00:22:38.570
tree to get any
kind of signal. [laughter] You know. So that's

00:22:38.570 --> 00:22:40.920
been very
instrumental to helping me read which helps

00:22:40.920 --> 00:22:41.920
me write.

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:42.920
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: How often do you do that.

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:45.320
&gt;&gt; Gary: I spent most of the fall up there.
I teach one

00:22:45.320 --> 00:22:47.870
semester at Columbia so this --. The next
four months are going to

00:22:47.870 --> 00:22:51.730
be here in New York. And that's -- not much
is going to

00:22:51.730 --> 00:22:55.760
get done -- a lot of distractions. And the
iPhone and

00:22:55.760 --> 00:22:57.680
New York together -- why live?

00:22:57.680 --> 00:22:58.680
[laughter]

00:22:58.680 --> 00:23:03.610
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: So I figured we could
probably start taking some

00:23:03.610 --> 00:23:06.550
audience questions. So feel free to come up
to the mics

00:23:06.550 --> 00:23:07.550
if you have any.

00:23:07.550 --> 00:23:09.270
&gt;&gt; Gary: I'll answer anything.

00:23:09.270 --> 00:23:13.751
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Hi. Thanks for coming to talk to
us. Really

00:23:13.751 --> 00:23:19.450
appreciate it. I love the book. I bought three
copies

00:23:19.450 --> 00:23:20.450
so you're welcome.

00:23:20.450 --> 00:23:22.250
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Gary: I'm eating steak because of you

00:23:22.250 --> 00:23:27.060
&gt;&gt; Male #1: And so, after I read it, I was
like it's a really brilliant

00:23:27.060 --> 00:23:29.990
book. I went to Amazon. Let's see what other
people had

00:23:29.990 --> 00:23:33.800
to say about it. I think what surprised me
is the comments

00:23:33.800 --> 00:23:38.340
often fell into two camps. One camp was "this
book is

00:23:38.340 --> 00:23:41.400
totally unrealistic." I was like kind of misses
the

00:23:41.400 --> 00:23:45.370
point. [laughter] And then there was another
camp which thought it

00:23:45.370 --> 00:23:48.310
was supposed to be science fiction. It wasn't
future

00:23:48.310 --> 00:23:51.820
looking enough which I also thought missed
the point. I

00:23:51.820 --> 00:23:53.961
was kind of wondering if you anticipated either
of those

00:23:53.961 --> 00:23:57.040
things happening and what your reaction to
that was.

00:23:57.040 --> 00:24:01.660
&gt;&gt; Gary: Sure, that's a good question. You
know, I grew up on science fiction completely.

00:24:01.660 --> 00:24:05.990
Asimov's Science Fiction magazine, that was
my big nerd pleasure

00:24:05.990 --> 00:24:10.220
growing up. And I was much more in tune with
technology

00:24:10.220 --> 00:24:15.090
than I am right now. I had the first Commodore
64 on the block and the Atari 2600.

00:24:15.090 --> 00:24:18.760
Many of you don't even know what this is,
right? The Commodore 64, it was

00:24:18.760 --> 00:24:25.650
a big deal back then and the Apple 2E all
this crap. So

00:24:25.650 --> 00:24:29.430
I loved -- you know, I loved the idea of science
fiction.

00:24:29.430 --> 00:24:31.640
On the other hand, at this point I know nothing
about

00:24:31.640 --> 00:24:37.480
science. You know, my Stuyvesant four years
notwithstanding. So I had to hire an intern

00:24:37.480 --> 00:24:41.280
who is very
attractive. People call him the man-tern.

00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:44.000
All my female
friends fell in love with him. And the man-tern

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:48.970
had a science background, [laughter] taught
me all this stuff how a cell becomes a law,

00:24:48.970 --> 00:24:52.640
you know. But
the first version I had of this book was much

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:55.900
more
science fictiony than it is now. And my editor

00:24:55.900 --> 00:24:58.630
at Random
House, who you saw on the screen, said you

00:24:58.630 --> 00:25:01.820
don't really
know much about science do you? And it shows.

00:25:01.820 --> 00:25:04.950
But you do know about heartbreak so write
about that.

00:25:04.950 --> 00:25:07.770
And so,
the book became gradually less science fictiony.

00:25:07.770 --> 00:25:10.780
So, and
I'm glad that happened, because in a way it's

00:25:10.780 --> 00:25:13.370
writing to
my strengths. But I knew that this book would

00:25:13.370 --> 00:25:17.360
be a little
strange to position. Because there is a so-called

00:25:17.360 --> 00:25:20.400
ghetto
called literary fiction. And once your book

00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:23.010
is slotted
into that, you're not going to get any sales

00:25:23.010 --> 00:25:26.250
at Costco.
It's shocking that this made the times best

00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:29.950
seller list. You
know you really are making your audience.

00:25:29.950 --> 00:25:34.780
Seattle,
Brooklyn, Portland, parts of Boston. The research

00:25:34.780 --> 00:25:38.960
triangle. [laughter] You know, you're limiting
yourself. So, but

00:25:38.960 --> 00:25:41.400
this is a strange kind of hybrid animal because
it does

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:45.460
have some science fictiony elements. And a
lot of

00:25:45.460 --> 00:25:49.490
authors have been playing around with this
idea of genre. Jonathan Lethem's Motherless

00:25:49.490 --> 00:25:53.850
Brooklyn is a good example.
It's a detective story but it falls more within

00:25:53.850 --> 00:25:56.470
the realm
of literary fiction. The problem with literary

00:25:56.470 --> 00:25:58.340
fiction -- don't quote me on this except this
is on

00:25:58.340 --> 00:26:04.790
YouTube or whatever -- I find a lot of it
quite dull. I mean it's

00:26:04.790 --> 00:26:06.890
great to write about one's parents divorcing
in west

00:26:06.890 --> 00:26:09.840
Chester. It's an important topic. [laughter]
