okay [laughs] we'll put out a print run of
eight copies. [laughter] You

00:37:42.670 --> 00:37:45.630
mention Saunders. I'm one of the few people
that works

00:37:45.630 --> 00:37:49.040
in his genre. I love his work. I'm always
paired with

00:37:49.040 --> 00:37:51.890
him. I've done 100 readings with him in the
New York

00:37:51.890 --> 00:37:54.410
festival alone. We're considered the two people
crazy

00:37:54.410 --> 00:37:57.020
enough to work in this very strange build
your own genre

00:37:57.020 --> 00:38:00.680
right there. I think of Jonathan Swift. I
think his

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:08.560
satire was really hilarious. There's a great
Russian

00:38:08.560 --> 00:38:11.810
tradition of satire. Russia, as a perpetually
failed

00:38:11.810 --> 00:38:14.911
state, engendered some really funny humor.
Gogol, one

00:38:14.911 --> 00:38:19.970
of my premier Russian writers was my favorites.
The story that

00:38:19.970 --> 00:38:23.070
really got me started as a writer was called
“The Nose”. And it's about a

00:38:23.070 --> 00:38:25.920
nose that jumps off the face of a official
in 19th

00:38:25.920 --> 00:38:29.030
century St. Petersburg and takes on a life
of his own and

00:38:29.030 --> 00:38:34.610
the nose puts on a uniform and a tri-cornered
hat and

00:38:34.610 --> 00:38:37.130
starts walking around St. Petersburg and wooing
women and

00:38:37.130 --> 00:38:40.630
going to church and stuff like that. And it's
about 15

00:38:40.630 --> 00:38:43.960
pages, but it captures Russia more eloquently
than the

00:38:43.960 --> 00:38:47.570
novels that are thousands of pages long. So
inspirations

00:38:47.570 --> 00:38:49.980
like that. And then, also the sort of Soviet
Jewish

00:38:49.980 --> 00:38:53.740
humor that I have. I would call it humor from
the edge

00:38:53.740 --> 00:38:57.400
of the grave, the humor of living in a country
that doesn't

00:38:57.400 --> 00:39:00.220
provide very much opportunities for joy but
at the same

00:39:00.220 --> 00:39:02.600
time trying to create your own joy by taking
the

00:39:02.600 --> 00:39:05.450
dystopian elements around you and mercilessly
making fun

00:39:05.450 --> 00:39:07.370
of them. This book was actual harder to write
than

00:39:07.370 --> 00:39:09.340
Absurdistan and the Russian Débutante's Handbook
, because

00:39:09.340 --> 00:39:12.130
those two previous novels were about the collapse
of the

00:39:12.130 --> 00:39:15.531
Soviet Union in a way. In this, you know,
I was never a

00:39:15.531 --> 00:39:17.910
great patriot of any country, when I was writing
this I

00:39:17.910 --> 00:39:22.480
was thinking, "wow, I always take America
for granted and

00:39:22.480 --> 00:39:25.030
if bad things happen to it, it happens to
me as well.

00:39:25.030 --> 00:39:28.560
It's different when it's not just some Absurdistan
on

00:39:28.560 --> 00:39:30.730
fire. It's different when it's your local
Duane Reade on

00:39:30.730 --> 00:39:35.270
fire. And that made me very sad when I wrote
this.

