00:49:49.510 --> 00:49:52.200
And love
changes the way, certain things about love

00:49:52.200 --> 00:49:55.270
changes. The
fact that we're texting and tweeting our potential

00:49:55.270 --> 00:49:57.700
mates
has changed. But at the same time the actual

00:49:57.700 --> 00:50:02.250
biological
feeling is the same. The need for romance,

00:50:02.250 --> 00:50:05.890
which is also
a part of the biological neurological aspects.

00:50:05.890 --> 00:50:08.190
Reproductive urges. All of that remains pretty
much the

00:50:08.190 --> 00:50:13.340
same. Fahrenheit 451 is a great example. The
book is

00:50:13.340 --> 00:50:16.490
about -- theoretically it's about a book burning
society,

00:50:16.490 --> 00:50:19.550
right? It's about a society that says books
are the

00:50:19.550 --> 00:50:21.730
problem and they have to be burned. But when
you read it

00:50:21.730 --> 00:50:26.530
closely, it's not really about that; it's
more about people don't want to read books.

00:50:26.530 --> 00:50:28.770
The society doesn't have to enforce the book
burning.

00:50:28.770 --> 00:50:31.100
There's very few books left. Everyone has
four screens

00:50:31.100 --> 00:50:35.060
that they have put on their walls and they're
communicating with those screens all the time.

00:50:35.060 --> 00:50:38.240
They
don't have any interior lives. Everything

00:50:38.240 --> 00:50:41.410
is led in a
public way. So when Bradbury was writing this

00:50:41.410 --> 00:50:44.790
40 years
ago, he's already talking about the present

00:50:44.790 --> 00:50:49.190
as we know it
now even though much of the book seems outdated

00:50:49.190 --> 00:50:52.040
it
continues to live on in our minds.

00:50:52.040 --> 00:50:57.720
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Hey, so having read your work excerpted
in the New

00:50:57.720 --> 00:51:01.420
Yorker, you know, effectively becomes short
fiction, but

00:51:01.420 --> 00:51:06.100
it's obviously part of a longer novel. And
you know

00:51:06.100 --> 00:51:09.600
written as part of the longer novel. Have
you considered

00:51:09.600 --> 00:51:11.670
writing something specifically short fiction?
Would you

00:51:11.670 --> 00:51:15.320
see that has being kind of a way of addressing
the more

00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:18.520
limited time that people have to devote to
books.

00:51:18.520 --> 00:51:21.910
&gt;&gt; Gary: This is one of the strangest things
in publishing that

00:51:21.910 --> 00:51:24.800
I really can't make heads or tails of. If
people's

00:51:24.800 --> 00:51:27.840
attention spans are waning and it's getting
harder and

00:51:27.840 --> 00:51:30.160
harder for people to concentrate, wouldn't
you think that

00:51:30.160 --> 00:51:34.430
the short story collections and the short
story genre

00:51:34.430 --> 00:51:39.430
would profit from this? That there would be
a resurgence? The very opposite has happened.

00:51:39.430 --> 00:51:41.680
The sales of short fiction with a few exceptions
--

00:51:41.680 --> 00:51:46.270
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Kindle singles now like
a whole new genre of shorter.

00:51:46.270 --> 00:51:48.890
&gt;&gt; Gary: I don't know what the sales of that
are but the sales

00:51:48.890 --> 00:51:53.610
of printed collections -- and they're also
available on

00:51:53.610 --> 00:51:58.041
kindle and E book have been plummeting completely.
Good

00:51:58.041 --> 00:52:01.590
example of that is Don DeLillo. I mean, Jesus
Christ, Don DeLillo has just published

00:52:01.590 --> 00:52:04.600
this amazing collection of short stories that
had not

00:52:04.600 --> 00:52:06.750
enjoyed the kind of sales you would except
from a

00:52:06.750 --> 00:52:10.230
Don DeLillo novel. I don't know what to make
sense of

00:52:10.230 --> 00:52:13.630
that. Why would people not want to read something
much

00:52:13.630 --> 00:52:17.350
shorter you know? And I think part of it is
also that

00:52:17.350 --> 00:52:19.790
the New Yorker -- you've mentioned the New
Yorker -- they

00:52:19.790 --> 00:52:23.210
still do short fiction, but almost every major
outlet in America has

00:52:23.210 --> 00:52:27.680
stopped doing it. The Atlantic has now just
one fiction

00:52:27.680 --> 00:52:30.460
issue. They crammed it all into one month.
I don't know

00:52:30.460 --> 00:52:32.480
how many people read that, but it used to
be -- Atlantic

00:52:32.480 --> 00:52:37.800
fiction used to be a major part of the literary
landscape. So

00:52:37.800 --> 00:52:41.810
weirdly enough short fiction hasn't benefited
from this. I don't know why.

00:52:41.810 --> 00:52:44.530
I think maybe people do still want a novel
because it's a

00:52:44.530 --> 00:52:48.210
fully immersive experience. You go into this
whole crazy

00:52:48.210 --> 00:52:53.170
world. So in a sense, it's kind of like entering
an interactive World of Warlocks game except

00:52:53.170 --> 00:52:55.330
you don't get to shoot anyone.

00:52:55.330 --> 00:53:00.220
&gt;&gt; Male #7: Sure. You can obviously do that
in short fiction effectively

00:53:00.220 --> 00:53:04.720
as well. And I'm also just curious personally
aside from

00:53:04.720 --> 00:53:07.640
commercial reasons, do you have a reason for
preferring

00:53:07.640 --> 00:53:08.640
writing novels.

00:53:08.640 --> 00:53:11.420
&gt;&gt;Gary: I suck at short stories. I really
do. I can't shut

00:53:11.420 --> 00:53:15.110
up. I've written maybe two or three in my
life that have

00:53:15.110 --> 00:53:17.700
been published. They're very long. They're
30, 40 pages

00:53:17.700 --> 00:53:21.850
long. I just don't know when to stop. Actually
being a

00:53:21.850 --> 00:53:24.500
short story writer requires greater skills
I think than being a

00:53:24.500 --> 00:53:26.390
novelist because you have to create the entire
world

00:53:26.390 --> 00:53:29.070
within the span of 20 pages. I don't have
those skills.

00:53:29.070 --> 00:53:32.290
George Saunders does. So if you want to go
read short

00:53:32.290 --> 00:53:35.080
satiric fiction that completely explains the
American

00:53:35.080 --> 00:53:38.460
condition today go to him. And just buy my
book anyway

00:53:38.460 --> 00:53:39.620
and burn it or something.

00:53:39.620 --> 00:53:40.620
[laughter]

00:53:40.620 --> 00:53:41.930
&gt;&gt; Male #7: Thanks.

00:53:41.930 --> 00:53:48.300
&gt;&gt; Male #8: Can I turn it around a little
bit? Because it's sort

00:53:48.300 --> 00:53:51.460
of -- yep. You've been saying how it's the
audience's

00:53:51.460 --> 00:53:55.660
not reading but my feeling is also it's hard
to find

00:53:55.660 --> 00:54:00.119
books that are compelling and they're not
either written

00:54:00.119 --> 00:54:03.869
for the 3,000 audience where it's impossible
to plow

00:54:03.869 --> 00:54:07.450
through them or they're not written to be
sold in

00:54:07.450 --> 00:54:10.820
Wal-Mart. So you know your book was actually
an

00:54:10.820 --> 00:54:11.820
exception for me.

00:54:11.820 --> 00:54:16.270
&gt;&gt; Gary: Well, thank you. I'm trying to find
that middle ground

00:54:16.270 --> 00:54:21.470
between the 3,000 readers and the larger -- and
the

00:54:21.470 --> 00:54:25.100
Wal-Mart bin where those products just stack
up and are

00:54:25.100 --> 00:54:29.540
moved out etcetera . I wonder, you know, and
I think about

00:54:29.540 --> 00:54:32.060
this a lot because I teach at an MFA program
and there

00:54:32.060 --> 00:54:36.340
are about 400 MFA programs out there in America.
Well,

00:54:36.340 --> 00:54:41.090
English departments can't find students to
learn about

00:54:41.090 --> 00:54:44.230
English literature-- American literature.
Creative writing

00:54:44.230 --> 00:54:47.570
programs are overflowing. Everybody wants
to write. Do

00:54:47.570 --> 00:54:49.260
we create -- and this is the question I always
ask

00:54:49.260 --> 00:54:53.570
myself -- do we create a specific kind of
writer, an MFA writer -- somebody who has

00:54:53.570 --> 00:54:58.940
a certain approach to literature where, you
know, and MFA

00:54:58.940 --> 00:55:04.230
programs all hone the same things characters,
craft etcetera, etcetera. Are we creating

00:55:04.230 --> 00:55:07.870
stories that are too similar? I
don't know. It's a good question. If you look

00:55:07.870 --> 00:55:10.140
at that
New Yorker 20 under 40 list almost every one

00:55:10.140 --> 00:55:13.680
of us has an
MFA. It's very rare for contemporary writers

00:55:13.680 --> 00:55:17.380
. In the
old days your MFA was you went to Spanish

00:55:17.380 --> 00:55:20.400
civil war and
got your leg shot off and then you wrote about

00:55:20.400 --> 00:55:24.200
it. [laughter] Now
you go to Iowa and hang around with 12 other

00:55:24.200 --> 00:55:27.300
middle class
people and then you write about that. So it's

00:55:27.300 --> 00:55:33.260
quite a
difference. Are we producing a class of people

00:55:33.260 --> 00:55:34.990
that are
writing the same thing? Well, looking at that

00:55:34.990 --> 00:55:37.870
list of 20
under 40, I would say no. And one of the interesting

00:55:37.870 --> 00:55:40.620
things how many of those people on those lists
do come

00:55:40.620 --> 00:55:42.930
from foreign countries and are writing about
experiences

00:55:42.930 --> 00:55:49.240
that are not within the norm of typical American
background. You have Rivka Galchen who grew

00:55:49.240 --> 00:55:57.510
up in Israel among other
places. You have Téa Obreht from Yugoslavia,

00:55:57.510 --> 00:56:01.750
the former Yugoslavia.
I think ten out of 20 or something like that

00:56:01.750 --> 00:56:05.180
were born
abroad. That's what's so exceptional about

00:56:05.180 --> 00:56:07.900
American
literature as opposed to other literatures

00:56:07.900 --> 00:56:11.140
the way we do
welcome in people in from – speaking of

00:56:11.140 --> 00:56:13.720
short stories, one of the biggest best sellers
in literary fiction

00:56:13.720 --> 00:56:17.110
was Jhumpa Lahiri's Interpreter of Maladies.
That sold over a million

00:56:17.110 --> 00:56:20.730
copies of short stories about Bengali immigrants
in

00:56:20.730 --> 00:56:24.520
Massachusetts. So it's interesting to see.
I think

00:56:24.520 --> 00:56:26.550
there is a lot of talent out there. The other
thing is

00:56:26.550 --> 00:56:29.050
we're publishing everything that moves. The
publishing

00:56:29.050 --> 00:56:33.220
industry is basically throwing darts at a
board hoping something will hit. For a

00:56:33.220 --> 00:56:36.680
reader you walk into a store you're surrounded
by

00:56:36.680 --> 00:56:38.780
gazillions of books. We're publishing something
like

00:56:38.780 --> 00:56:42.840
200,000 books. How do you choose? Except for
things

00:56:42.840 --> 00:56:46.970
like the New Yorker or the New York Times
or GoodReads or whatever it is.

00:56:46.970 --> 00:56:50.510
It's almost -- there's an embarrassment of
riches. I

00:56:50.510 --> 00:56:53.640
almost wish there were fewer writers but they
wrote the

00:56:53.640 --> 00:56:58.630
stuff you want. Which is not the Wal-Mart
bin and not

00:56:58.630 --> 00:57:00.359
the 3,000 either.

00:57:00.359 --> 00:57:04.310
&gt;&gt; Male #8: Right and I hope that you don't
think the answer is

00:57:04.310 --> 00:57:08.520
working for HBO, because frankly, it's so
limiting. How

00:57:08.520 --> 00:57:11.050
many of these things can be produced in a
year. And

00:57:11.050 --> 00:57:15.359
they're driven by, you know, the audience.

00:57:15.359 --> 00:57:19.580
&gt;&gt; Gary: Very few. I would say of all the
writers writing -- I

00:57:19.580 --> 00:57:21.680
think maybe 2 percent of us will actually
make it into

00:57:21.680 --> 00:57:24.859
production. The scripts are commissioned,
but not

00:57:24.859 --> 00:57:29.080
necessarily be made. I think if it's good,
it's really

00:57:29.080 --> 00:57:32.260
good. I think the Wire explained life in the
American

00:57:32.260 --> 00:57:34.830
urban underclass better than any other book
-- it's not

00:57:34.830 --> 00:57:37.200
book -- better than any book I've encountered
maybe with

00:57:37.200 --> 00:57:42.190
one exception. Random Family, Adriene Nicole
LeBlanc, a woman who graduated from Brown

00:57:42.190 --> 00:57:45.150
and spent ten
years living with this south Bronx family.

00:57:45.150 --> 00:57:49.200
Other than
that I can't think of any other art form that

00:57:49.200 --> 00:57:51.490
has allowed
me to connect with a world which I know nothing

00:57:51.490 --> 00:57:54.600
about.
So hats off to the Wire and things like that.

00:57:54.600 --> 00:57:57.740
But you're
right for every Wire there's a bunch of shows

00:57:57.740 --> 00:57:59.369
that
obviously are sub par.

00:57:59.369 --> 00:58:01.520
&gt;&gt; Male #8: I look forward to your next book.

00:58:01.520 --> 00:58:02.520
&gt;&gt;Gary: Thank you.

00:58:02.520 --> 00:58:05.840
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: I have one last question.
With all the -- you mention

00:58:05.840 --> 00:58:10.501
that the capacity for love has not changed.
But do you

00:58:10.501 --> 00:58:13.750
ever think that with all the technology just
these

00:58:13.750 --> 00:58:17.470
succinct forms of communication and incomplete
sentences

00:58:17.470 --> 00:58:22.580
and thoughts that that's kind of leading to
-- like, a

00:58:22.580 --> 00:58:24.810
lack or inability to commit to things?

00:58:24.810 --> 00:58:28.450
&gt;&gt; Sure. I mean, I think because we have so
many choices

00:58:28.450 --> 00:58:30.900
in every aspect of our lives at this point.
I mean, the

00:58:30.900 --> 00:58:34.780
iPhone is a device of choices. I want to walk
to ninth

00:58:34.780 --> 00:58:36.180
street. Well, there's four different ways
to get there

00:58:36.180 --> 00:58:39.320
and the computer is telling me you can do
it through

00:58:39.320 --> 00:58:43.520
route A, route B, route C, route D. The iPhone
doesn't

00:58:43.520 --> 00:58:45.990
have any sense of nostalgia. It doesn't remember
that

00:58:45.990 --> 00:58:51.190
the first time I kissed someone was along
route B and

00:58:51.190 --> 00:58:55.190
that makes a difference. In Super Sad, at
one point, Lenny is trying to

00:58:55.190 --> 00:58:58.290
read to Eunice as a way of creating a sense
of communication between them. He's trying

00:58:58.290 --> 00:59:01.090
to read Kundera's Unbearable Lightness of
Being. And

00:59:01.090 --> 00:59:02.950
she begins to cry because she just doesn't
understand

00:59:02.950 --> 00:59:05.670
what he's doing. She doesn't understand what
the value

00:59:05.670 --> 00:59:09.100
of this is. She's used to direct communications.
Being

00:59:09.100 --> 00:59:12.250
told what to do in a way, either by other
people who are

00:59:12.250 --> 00:59:15.190
on the Internet or by the giant corporations
that move

00:59:15.190 --> 00:59:18.770
the Internet along. She's unused to the idea
of having a

00:59:18.770 --> 00:59:22.030
kind of intellectual, non-pornographic encounter
with

00:59:22.030 --> 00:59:26.150
somebody. It's completely new to her. And
the result is

00:59:26.150 --> 00:59:28.630
very sad, I think, for both of them. In that
part of the

00:59:28.630 --> 00:59:33.490
book it becomes clear this relationship may
not work out.

00:59:33.490 --> 00:59:36.200
People say love will find a way. But let's
hope so.

00:59:36.200 --> 00:59:40.470
Let's hope there's actual personal encounters.
Physical

00:59:40.470 --> 00:59:43.840
encounters for God's sakes and that we don't
just retreat

00:59:43.840 --> 00:59:47.280
where it's safest. Because sitting at home
with the

00:59:47.280 --> 00:59:52.160
computer is very safe. Sure people can send
-- I always

00:59:52.160 --> 00:59:56.380
get angry tweets and Facebookings and e-mails,
you know,

00:59:56.380 --> 01:00:02.270
you're such a schmuck. This is a bad hair
day, etcetera. But

01:00:02.270 --> 01:00:05.100
it's safer than actually seeing people and
falling in

01:00:05.100 --> 01:00:07.050
love with them the old fashioned way.

01:00:07.050 --> 01:00:10.240
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Okay. Well, thank you
for joining us Gary.

01:00:10.240 --> 01:00:11.160
&gt;&gt;Gary: Well, thank-you so much
